---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MascotTip from '../../components/MascotTip.astro';
import AuthorByline from '../../components/AuthorByline.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import FAQSection from '../../components/FAQSection.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How to Pay Rent with a Credit Card and Earn Points (2026 Guide) | ProofLabs"
  description="Earn 30,000+ points per year on rent using BILT. Tyler breaks down exactly how it works, which BILT card to use, and the math."
>
  <article style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 8rem 0 4rem;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text); line-height: 1.1;">
      How to Pay Rent with a Credit Card and Earn Points
    </h1>

    <AuthorByline date="March 15, 2026" />

    <div style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      
      <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); margin: 2rem 0;">
        For most people, rent is their single biggest monthly expense. And for years, it was dead money — no rewards, no points, nothing.
      </p>

      <p>
        I pay $2,500/month in rent. That's $30,000 per year going to my landlord. Until I discovered BILT, every dollar was completely unoptimized.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now? That same $30,000 earns me 30,000 BILT points annually. Zero fees. Zero extra cost. Same rent payment, but now it generates $300-600 in travel value (or more if I transfer to airline partners).
      </p>

      <p>
        Here's exactly how it works.
      </p>

      <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fed7aa 100%); border: 2px solid var(--color-accent); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 2rem; margin: 3rem 0; box-shadow: var(--shadow-md); text-align: center;">
        <div style="font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: var(--color-text); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
          30,000 Points/Year
        </div>
        <div style="font-size: 1rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          On $2,500/month rent • No fees • No extra steps
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        How BILT Works
      </h2>

      <p>
        BILT is a credit card designed specifically for rent payments. Unlike most cards that either charge 2-3% fees for rent or don't allow it at all, BILT lets you pay rent with zero transaction fees.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>The basics:</strong>
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Earn 1 point per dollar on rent (and other purchases)</li>
        <li>No fee to pay rent via credit card</li>
        <li>Works with any landlord (even if they don't accept cards)</li>
        <li>Transfer points to 100+ airline and hotel partners OR use toward rent credits, travel, or even a home down payment</li>
        <li>No annual fee</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The catch: You need to make at least 5 transactions per month on your BILT card for rent to earn points. This is easy — groceries, gas, coffee, whatever. Just use the card 5 times and your rent payment counts.
      </p>

      <MascotTip type="tip">
        <p>I set 5 recurring subscriptions to autopay on my BILT card (Netflix, Spotify, iCloud, etc.). That way I automatically hit the 5-transaction minimum every month without thinking about it.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        BILT 2.0 vs BILT Cash vs BILT Palladium
      </h2>

      <p>
        There are three BILT cards. Here's which one(s) to get:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); overflow-x: auto; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9375rem;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border);">
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Card</th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Rent Rewards</th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Other Rewards</th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Annual Fee</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">BILT Mastercard (2.0)</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1x points/dollar</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1-3x on other categories</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$0</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">BILT Cash</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1x points/dollar</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1% cashback everywhere</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$0</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">BILT Palladium</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1x points/dollar</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">1-3x on categories + perks</td>
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$0 (invite-only)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        <strong>My setup:</strong> I have both the BILT 2.0 and BILT Cash. I use the 2.0 for rent and everyday spending to accumulate points. I keep the Cash card as a backup for when I want straight cashback instead of points.
      </p>

      <p>
        For most people, start with BILT 2.0. It's the most flexible.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        The Math: What 30,000 Points Is Worth
      </h2>

      <p>
        Here's where it gets interesting. BILT points aren't cashback — they're transferable points. That means their value depends on how you use them.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Conservative value:</strong> $300-400/year  
        If you redeem for statement credits or rent discounts, BILT points are worth about 1-1.3 cents each. On $2,500/month rent ($30,000/year), that's 30,000 points = $300-400.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Optimized value:</strong> $600+/year  
        If you transfer to airline partners (American, United, Alaska, etc.) or hotel programs (Hyatt, IHG, Marriott), you can often get 2+ cents per point in value. That same 30,000 points could be worth $600+ in flights or hotel stays.
      </p>

      <p>
        Even at the conservative estimate, you're getting $300-400/year in value for literally doing nothing different. You were paying rent anyway.
      </p>

      <MascotTip type="pick">
        <p>I transfer my BILT points to Alaska Airlines and use them for West Coast flights. I've gotten roundtrip tickets to LA and San Diego that would've cost $300-400 cash for just 15,000-20,000 points. That's 2+ cents per point value — way better than redeeming for cashback.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Step-by-Step Setup
      </h2>

      <p>
        Getting started with BILT is straightforward:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Step 1: Apply for BILT Mastercard</h4>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <!-- TODO: Add affiliate link --> Visit bfrg.com and apply. Approval is instant for most people with good credit (700+).
        </p>

        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Step 2: Add Your Landlord</h4>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          In the BILT app, add your landlord's info (name and address). BILT will mail them a check each month. Your landlord doesn't need to do anything or even know you're using a credit card.
        </p>

        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Step 3: Set Up Autopay</h4>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          Schedule your rent payment to autopay each month. BILT sends the check 5-7 days before your due date so it arrives on time.
        </p>

        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Step 4: Make 5 Monthly Transactions</h4>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          Use your BILT card for at least 5 purchases per month (any amount). I set autopay on 5 subscriptions. Done.
        </p>

        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Step 5: Points Arrive Automatically</h4>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 0;">
          After your statement closes, your rent points post to your account. No extra steps. Transfer them whenever you're ready to use them.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Common Questions & Gotchas
      </h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Does my landlord need to accept credit cards?</strong><br/>
        Nope. BILT mails them a check. From their perspective, it's just a regular check in the mail each month.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Will this count as a cash advance?</strong><br/>
        No. BILT processes rent as a regular purchase, not a cash advance. No cash advance fees, no higher APR.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What if I forget the 5-transaction minimum?</strong><br/>
        You won't earn points on your rent for that month. Everything else (dining, travel, etc.) still earns points, but rent won't count. That's why I set autopay on 5 subscriptions — I never have to think about it.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Can I use other cards to pay rent?</strong><br/>
        Technically yes via services like Plastiq, but they charge 2.5-2.85% fees. On $2,500 rent, that's $62-71/month in fees ($744-852/year). Even a 2% cashback card would net you negative value after fees. BILT is the only major card with zero rent fees.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What if I move or my rent changes?</strong><br/>
        Just update the payment amount or landlord info in the BILT app. Takes 2 minutes.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        The Bottom Line
      </h2>

      <p>
        If you pay rent, get BILT. It's the only way to earn meaningful rewards on rent without paying fees.
      </p>

      <p>
        $2,500/month rent = 30,000 points/year = $300-600 in value (or more). Zero fees. Zero extra effort beyond hitting 5 transactions per month.
      </p>

      <p>
        I've been using BILT for over a year. It's completely effortless and adds $500-600/year in travel value to my budget that I wasn't getting before.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>

      <FAQSection faqs={[
        {
          question: "What credit score do I need to get approved for BILT?",
          answer: "BILT typically approves applicants with credit scores of 700+. If you have a shorter credit history or lower score, you might get approved for BILT Cash (the cashback version) first, then upgrade to the points card later."
        },
        {
          question: "Can I pay my mortgage with BILT?",
          answer: "Unfortunately no. BILT only works for rent payments, not mortgages. If you own your home, this strategy doesn't apply — focus on optimizing other spending categories instead."
        },
        {
          question: "How long does it take for my landlord to receive the check?",
          answer: "BILT sends the check 5-7 business days before your selected due date. In my experience, it arrives 3-5 days before the due date, giving plenty of buffer. I've never had a late payment."
        },
        {
          question: "What happens to my points if I stop renting?",
          answer: "Your points don't expire as long as your BILT account stays open. You can still use the card for regular purchases and keep accumulating points even if you're not paying rent. If you close the card, you'll need to use or transfer your points before closing."
        },
        {
          question: "Can I have multiple BILT cards?",
          answer: "Yes. I have both BILT 2.0 and BILT Cash. They share the same points balance (if you have the points versions), so you can use whichever makes sense for each purchase. Some people get all three (2.0, Cash, and Palladium if invited)."
        }
      ]} />

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Related Articles
      </h2>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem 0; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/credit-cards/best-credit-card-for-rent" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">Best Credit Card for Rent 2026</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/secret-sauce" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">How I Earn $3,500+/Year in Rewards</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/credit-card-stacking" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">Credit Card Stacking Guide</a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <EmailCapture
        variant="article-end"
        headline="Want the full rewards system?"
        description="Get Tyler's complete cash back stacking system — the spreadsheet, the card stack recommendations, and weekly deals."
        buttonText="Get free access"
      />

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
